      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Here is the paper you're looking for:\n\n## **Understanding LLM Behaviors via Compression: Data Generation, Knowledge Acquisition and Scaling Laws**\n\n**Authors:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Zhixuan Pan, Shaowen Wang, Jian Li"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**arXiv:** 2504.09597 — "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Submitted on 13 Apr 2025 (v1), last revised 9 Nov 2025 (v6)"
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Venue:** "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Published as a NeurIPS 2025 spotlight paper."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Summary\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "LLMs have demonstrated remarkable capabilities across numerous tasks, yet principled explanations for their underlying mechanisms — such as scaling laws, hallucinations, and related behaviors — remain elusive. This work revisits the classical relationship between compression and prediction, grounded in Kolmogorov complexity and Shannon information theory, to provide deeper insights into LLM behaviors."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "By leveraging the Kolmogorov Structure Function and interpreting LLM compression as a two-part coding process, the authors offer a detailed view of how LLMs acquire and store information across increasing model and data scales — from pervasive syntactic patterns to progressively rarer knowledge elements."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Motivated by this theoretical perspective and natural assumptions inspired by Heap's and Zipf's laws, they introduce a simplified yet representative hierarchical data-generation framework called the Syntax-Knowledge model."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n"
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Under the Bayesian setting, prediction and compression within this model naturally lead to diverse learning and scaling behaviors observed in LLMs. The theoretical analysis offers intuitive and principled explanations for both data and model scaling laws, the dynamics of knowledge acquisition during training and fine-tuning, and factual knowledge hallucinations in LLMs."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n### Key Findings\n\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "For a fixed model capacity, if a knowledge element appears with a frequency below a certain threshold, the model will choose not to learn it, despite having seen it many times during training."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n- "
      },
      {
        "citations": [],
        "type": "text",
        "text": "Hallucination tends to occur when the total amount of knowledge exceeds the model's capacity. For example, for a 7.2M-sized model, knowledge that occurs fewer than 508 times is consistently hallucinated, regardless of the number of pretraining epochs."
      },
      {
        "type": "text",
        "text": "\n\n**Links:**\n- arXiv: https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.09597\n- OpenReview: https://openreview.net/forum?id=853SwC2dMZ"
      }
    ],
